		<h2>POSTGRADUATE</h2><p>Postgraduate Studies at the Mackintosh School of Architecture is part of the creative community of architects, artists and designers known as the Glasgow School of Art.</p><p>Postgraduate studies are architecturally underpinned by the energy and thrust of a lively undergraduate and graduate programme and stimulated by on-going research into urban and housing design, energy, sustainability and environmental design, digital design and simulation, architectural and inter-disciplinary practice.  These creative foundations support postgraduate students in questions surfacing in the fields of urban design, urban buildings, computer aided architectural design and energy and environmental studies.</p><p>Fresh ideas are able to be pursued in the heart of a great European city  - Glasgow - European City of Culture in 1990 and City of Architecture &amp; Design in 1999, in dedicated studios overlooking an architectural masterpiece, Charles Rennie Mackintosh's Glasgow School of Art.</p><p>Applicants have a choice from three programmes of study and brief details on each are outlined below.  For detailed information on each of these programmes of study, please use the links on the left.</p><p><b>M.Arch (Taught)</b></p><p>The M.Arch (Taught) programme is structured to provide common ground for discourse, debate and shared activity to support individual projects developed within one of the four specialist areas. It is research and project driven with a multi-disciplinary input in the specialist areas of:</p><ul><li>Urban Design + Creative Urban Practices</li><li>Urban Building</li><li>Computer Aided Architectural Design</li><li>Energy &amp; Environmental Studies</li></ul><p>It is a full-time course of 1 calendar year.</p><p><b>M.Arch (by Research) </b></p><p>The M.Arch (by Research) programme demands a high level of academic rigour and the degree is awarded for work which demonstrates critical knowledge of and contains some element of original contribution to the chosen field of study.  It is a full-time programme of two years minimum or three years part-time. </p><p><b>Doctor of Philosophy</b></p><p>The Ph.D. programme is three years minimum full-time or four years part-time.  The degree is awarded for a work that makes a significant and original contribution to knowledge in the chosen area of investigation.</p><p>All three programmes allow students to take part in the life, lectures, debate and work within the Mackintosh School.  Students are encouraged to participate in reviews of student work and attend lectures and seminars within the Mackintosh School and, by agreement, elsewhere in the School of Art.</p>
	

	

	

	

	

	

	
	
	
	
	


	
	







